==English==

===Etymology===
Probably from {{etyl|ang}} [[cweolm]] (West Saxon) "death, disaster, plague," [[utcualm]] (Anglian) "utter destruction," related to [[cwellan]] "to kill," [[cwelan]] "to die". The other suggested etymology, less satisfying, is from {{etyl|nl}} [[kwalm]] "steam, vapor, mist," which also may be ultimately from the same Germanic root as [[quell]] Sense softened to "feeling of faintness" 1530; meaning "uneasiness, doubt" is from 1553; that of "scruple of conscience" is 1649. An indirect connection between the Old English and modern senses is plausible, via the notion of "fit of sickness."

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[sickly]] [[feeling]] of being [[ill at ease]]; sudden [[queasiness]].
# A prick of the [[conscience]], moral [[scrupul]].
# An uneasy feeling of [[apprehension]] and/or [[doubt]]

